JOHANNESBURG – South African Reserve Bank governor Lesetja Kganyago has been appointed chairman of the International Monetary and Financial Committee (IMFC). Lesetja will take on the role for a term of three years, effective from Thursday. He succeeds the former governor of the Bank of Mexico Agustín Carstens, who resigned from the role in December 2017 to assume the position of general manager of the Bank for International Settlements (BIS). WATCH: Interest rate kept the same The IMFC comprises finance ministers and central bank governors. It is the primary advisory body of the International Monetary Fund Board of Governors and deliberates on the principal policy issues facing the IMF.  eNCA